**Q2: How does Drift give type safety?**

**A:** Build-time code generation. You declare tables as annotated Dart classes:
```dart
class Users extends Table {
  IntColumn  get id => integer().autoIncrement()();
  TextColumn get email => text().unique()();
}
```
`build_runner` reads this + generates `User` (row model), `UsersCompanion` (insert/update model), typed `SimpleSelectStatement<Users, User>` builders. Column references become properties: `users.email.equals('...')` — auto-complete, refactor-safe. Rename `email` in the schema → all references either update via IDE refactor or fail to compile. **Contrast with raw SQL strings:** `'SELECT eamil FROM users'` compiles fine and crashes at runtime. Drift eliminates this whole class of bugs.
